1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,803
*The base rate is 2.5%*.

2
00:00:01,803 --> 00:00:03,757
And it’s staying there.

3
00:00:03,757 --> 00:00:05,410
But that feels a little strange, doesn’t it?

4
00:00:05,410 --> 00:00:06,913
If rates aren’t going up,

5
00:00:06,913 --> 00:00:09,919
then home prices should be rising again.

6
00:00:09,919 --> 00:00:11,121
But in reality,

7
00:00:11,121 --> 00:00:13,225
it’s not that simple.

8
00:00:13,225 --> 00:00:14,427
Here’s where the market stands right now.

9
00:00:14,427 --> 00:00:16,230
There’s something the market watches,

10
00:00:16,230 --> 00:00:18,484
even more closely than interest rates.

11
00:00:18,484 --> 00:00:19,987
Today,

12
00:00:19,987 --> 00:00:21,640
let’s break that down in simple terms.

13
00:00:21,640 --> 00:00:24,195
A lot of people think like this:

14
00:00:24,195 --> 00:00:26,600
If rates aren’t going any higher now,

15
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:29,005
doesn’t that mean real estate should start recovering too?

16
00:00:29,005 --> 00:00:31,560
That’s a completely reasonable thought.

17
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:33,664
When the base rate stops rising,

18
00:00:33,664 --> 00:00:36,069
people naturally expect sentiment to improve first.

19
00:00:36,069 --> 00:00:38,624
It feels like the burden of interest payments should ease,

20
00:00:38,624 --> 00:00:41,179
and buying activity should start picking up again.

21
00:00:41,179 --> 00:00:42,381
But the market

22
00:00:42,381 --> 00:00:44,034
is colder than people expect.

23
00:00:44,034 --> 00:00:45,537
It’s hard to say

24
00:00:45,537 --> 00:00:47,040
that home prices overall

25
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:48,543
are making a strong comeback.

26
00:00:48,543 --> 00:00:49,595
Why is that?

27
00:00:49,595 --> 00:00:51,098
The reason is simple.

28
00:00:51,098 --> 00:00:53,954
The market cares less about the *rate pause* itself,

29
00:00:53,954 --> 00:00:56,058
and more about what that pause is actually signaling.

30
00:00:56,058 --> 00:00:58,463
Let’s start with the bigger picture first.

31
00:00:58,463 --> 00:01:00,567
If the base rate stays at 2.5%,

32
00:01:00,567 --> 00:01:03,573
that usually means the Bank of Korea

33
00:01:03,573 --> 00:01:04,925
is still watching carefully

34
00:01:04,925 --> 00:01:06,728
between inflation and the economy.

35
00:01:06,728 --> 00:01:09,433
Put simply,

36
00:01:09,433 --> 00:01:10,485
the economy isn’t strong enough yet

37
00:01:10,485 --> 00:01:12,138
to justify a major easing of money.

38
00:01:12,138 --> 00:01:14,392
But on the other hand,

39
00:01:14,392 --> 00:01:16,947
inflation isn’t unstable enough

40
00:01:16,947 --> 00:01:19,352
to justify another rate hike either.

41
00:01:19,352 --> 00:01:21,456
In other words, we’re in a gray area.

42
00:01:21,456 --> 00:01:22,959
At times like this, people focus less on the fact

43
00:01:22,959 --> 00:01:25,063
that rates have paused,

44
00:01:25,063 --> 00:01:27,017
and more on whether their income will rise,

45
00:01:27,017 --> 00:01:28,820
whether the economy will really recover,

46
00:01:28,820 --> 00:01:31,525
and whether they can actually afford to buy a home right now.

47
00:01:31,525 --> 00:01:33,328
That’s the first calculation they make.

48
00:01:33,328 --> 00:01:34,380
In the end, the market

49
00:01:34,380 --> 00:01:36,484
doesn’t just look at one rate number.

50
00:01:36,484 --> 00:01:39,039
It looks at your *ability to hold up* going forward.

51
00:01:39,039 --> 00:01:41,293
And here’s something important.

52
00:01:41,293 --> 00:01:43,247
What really matters is the *mortgage rate*.

53
00:01:43,247 --> 00:01:44,299
A lot of people

54
00:01:44,299 --> 00:01:45,802
only look at the base rate.

55
00:01:45,802 --> 00:01:47,455
But when you’re buying a home,

56
00:01:47,455 --> 00:01:49,108
what you actually feel

57
00:01:49,108 --> 00:01:50,761
isn’t the base rate itself.

58
00:01:50,761 --> 00:01:51,963
What matters more is

59
00:01:51,963 --> 00:01:53,917
how much you can borrow

60
00:01:53,917 --> 00:01:55,570
and at what rate from the bank.

61
00:01:55,570 --> 00:01:57,373
Even if the base rate stays the same,

62
00:01:57,373 --> 00:01:59,477
if actual mortgage rates

63
00:01:59,477 --> 00:02:01,280
don’t come down quickly,

64
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:03,985
buyer sentiment won’t recover easily.

65
00:02:03,985 --> 00:02:05,337
That’s because banks

66
00:02:05,337 --> 00:02:06,689
don’t set lending rates

67
00:02:06,689 --> 00:02:09,545
based only on the base rate.

68
00:02:09,545 --> 00:02:11,799
They also have to consider funding costs,

69
00:02:11,799 --> 00:02:13,151
added spreads get layered on,

70
00:02:13,151 --> 00:02:15,556
and regulations come into play too.

71
00:02:15,556 --> 00:02:18,712
Especially rules like *stress DSR*,

72
00:02:18,712 --> 00:02:20,666
which can directly change

73
00:02:20,666 --> 00:02:21,718
how much you’re allowed to borrow.

74
00:02:21,718 --> 00:02:23,221
So people

75
00:02:23,221 --> 00:02:26,077
don’t buy homes

76
00:02:26,077 --> 00:02:28,031
just because they see a 2.5% base rate.

77
00:02:28,031 --> 00:02:29,083
What matters is

78
00:02:29,083 --> 00:02:31,037
how much they can actually borrow,

79
00:02:31,037 --> 00:02:32,089
and how much interest

80
00:02:32,089 --> 00:02:33,742
they’ll have to pay every month.

81
00:02:33,742 --> 00:02:35,846
That number matters more.

82
00:02:35,846 --> 00:02:36,747
The market always

83
00:02:36,747 --> 00:02:38,701
responds to the rate people actually feel.

84
00:02:38,701 --> 00:02:40,204
More than the rate in the headlines,

85
00:02:40,204 --> 00:02:42,458
it reacts to the pressure in your bank account.

86
00:02:42,458 --> 00:02:44,261
The next thing to watch

87
00:02:44,261 --> 00:02:45,613
is *transaction volume*.

88
00:02:45,613 --> 00:02:47,867
This indicator really matters.

89
00:02:47,867 --> 00:02:49,520
From the outside, prices

90
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:52,225
can look like they’re holding up.

91
00:02:52,225 --> 00:02:53,878
Listings may not be falling,

92
00:02:53,878 --> 00:02:56,884
and distressed sales may even seem to be fading.

93
00:02:56,884 --> 00:02:59,589
But if transaction volume doesn’t recover,

94
00:02:59,589 --> 00:03:01,843
the market is still running cold.

95
00:03:01,843 --> 00:03:02,744
Put simply,

96
00:03:02,744 --> 00:03:04,247
prices may be standing still,

97
00:03:04,247 --> 00:03:07,704
but people still aren’t actually buying.

98
00:03:07,704 --> 00:03:09,658
And that matters a lot.

99
00:03:09,658 --> 00:03:11,612
Because in the end,

100
00:03:11,612 --> 00:03:14,317
the direction of the market is revealed by actual transactions.

101
00:03:14,317 --> 00:03:15,369
Not by talk,

102
00:03:15,369 --> 00:03:16,872
but by deals getting done.

103
00:03:16,872 --> 00:03:18,224
Not by the mood,

104
00:03:18,224 --> 00:03:20,178
but by actual buying behavior.

105
00:03:20,178 --> 00:03:22,282
If transaction volume doesn’t back it up,

106
00:03:22,282 --> 00:03:25,288
a price rebound won’t spread broadly.

107
00:03:25,288 --> 00:03:27,242
Prices may hold for a while,

108
00:03:27,242 --> 00:03:29,196
but it’s hard for that to turn into a trend.

109
00:03:29,196 --> 00:03:30,548
Especially end-users

110
00:03:30,548 --> 00:03:32,953
are much more cautious than before.

111
00:03:32,953 --> 00:03:34,756
They don’t just look at rates.

112
00:03:34,756 --> 00:03:36,710
They check how much they can borrow,

113
00:03:36,710 --> 00:03:38,363
look at local supply conditions,

114
00:03:38,363 --> 00:03:40,768
and watch the direction of lease prices too.

115
00:03:40,768 --> 00:03:42,722
If I buy this home,

116
00:03:42,722 --> 00:03:44,225
will jeonse demand support the price?

117
00:03:44,225 --> 00:03:45,878
Is there a large number of new units coming in?

118
00:03:45,878 --> 00:03:47,681
Not just whether prices will rise,

119
00:03:47,681 --> 00:03:49,334
but whether the cash flow makes sense.

120
00:03:49,334 --> 00:03:50,837
They look at all of that together.

121
00:03:50,837 --> 00:03:53,091
So just because a few preferred areas

122
00:03:53,091 --> 00:03:55,045
are holding up or going higher,

123
00:03:55,045 --> 00:03:56,999
it’s hard to say right away

124
00:03:56,999 --> 00:03:58,953
that the whole market is recovering.

125
00:03:58,953 --> 00:04:00,606
Looking at the market as a whole,

126
00:04:00,606 --> 00:04:01,958
it’s hard to say

127
00:04:01,958 --> 00:04:04,964
that a bull market has started

128
00:04:04,964 --> 00:04:06,918
just because rates have paused.

129
00:04:06,918 --> 00:04:09,473
That’s how selective

130
00:04:09,473 --> 00:04:10,976
today’s market has become.

131
00:04:10,976 --> 00:04:12,178
If you think of actual examples,

132
00:04:12,178 --> 00:04:13,981
it becomes even clearer.

133
00:04:13,981 --> 00:04:15,784
Even under the same rate environment,

134
00:04:15,784 --> 00:04:17,136
prime areas in Seoul and the outskirts

135
00:04:17,136 --> 00:04:18,488
react differently.

136
00:04:18,488 --> 00:04:19,840
The Seoul metro area and regional cities

137
00:04:19,840 --> 00:04:21,493
react differently too.

138
00:04:21,493 --> 00:04:23,296
In places where demand is concentrated,

139
00:04:23,296 --> 00:04:24,648
even a small pickup in transactions

140
00:04:24,648 --> 00:04:26,151
can help prices hold up.

141
00:04:26,151 --> 00:04:28,556
Because those are places

142
00:04:28,556 --> 00:04:30,660
people already want to buy.

143
00:04:30,660 --> 00:04:31,862
On the other hand, in weaker-demand areas,

144
00:04:31,862 --> 00:04:33,966
even if rates pause,

145
00:04:33,966 --> 00:04:35,619
transactions still don’t pick up easily.

146
00:04:35,619 --> 00:04:38,324
Because there are more people hesitating

147
00:04:38,324 --> 00:04:40,879
than people eager to buy.

148
00:04:40,879 --> 00:04:41,931
And that reveals the core of the market.

149
00:04:41,931 --> 00:04:42,983
Right now,

150
00:04:42,983 --> 00:04:45,388
this is not a market

151
00:04:45,388 --> 00:04:46,740
where everything moves together

152
00:04:46,740 --> 00:04:48,092
based on rates alone.

153
00:04:48,092 --> 00:04:49,595
It’s a market splitting apart

154
00:04:49,595 --> 00:04:50,346
based on *purchasing power*

155
00:04:50,346 --> 00:04:52,300
and *location*.

156
00:04:52,300 --> 00:04:53,803
In short,

157
00:04:53,803 --> 00:04:56,358
it’s a highly selective market.

158
00:04:56,358 --> 00:04:58,763
Strong areas hold up,

159
00:04:58,763 --> 00:04:59,965
while weaker areas remain cautious.

160
00:04:59,965 --> 00:05:01,768
And that gap is only getting wider.

161
00:05:01,768 --> 00:05:03,120
So now,

162
00:05:03,120 --> 00:05:04,923
we need to change the question.

163
00:05:04,923 --> 00:05:06,726
Rates have paused,

164
00:05:06,726 --> 00:05:08,830
so why aren’t home prices rising?

165
00:05:08,830 --> 00:05:11,235
That’s an important question too.

166
00:05:11,235 --> 00:05:13,489
But the more important question is:

167
00:05:13,489 --> 00:05:15,593
which areas respond first?

168
00:05:15,593 --> 00:05:17,246
Who moves first?

169
00:05:17,246 --> 00:05:19,651
Where demand with real cash capacity

170
00:05:19,651 --> 00:05:20,402
starts coming back first,

171
00:05:20,402 --> 00:05:22,356
where lending is actually loosening in practice,

172
00:05:22,356 --> 00:05:22,957
where lease prices are providing support,

173
00:05:22,957 --> 00:05:24,911
and where supply pressure is lower.

174
00:05:24,911 --> 00:05:25,512
That’s what we need to watch.

175
00:05:25,512 --> 00:05:27,015
The market now

176
00:05:27,015 --> 00:05:28,067
can’t be explained

177
00:05:28,067 --> 00:05:30,772
by a one-line headline anymore.

178
00:05:30,772 --> 00:05:32,275
There was a time

179
00:05:32,275 --> 00:05:34,830
when one line about the base rate

180
00:05:34,830 --> 00:05:36,784
could move the whole market.

181
00:05:36,784 --> 00:05:38,888
But not anymore.

182
00:05:38,888 --> 00:05:39,940
Now the picture is much more complex.

183
00:05:39,940 --> 00:05:41,142
Interest rates and lending,

184
00:05:41,142 --> 00:05:42,795
transaction volume and supply-demand,

185
00:05:42,795 --> 00:05:44,147
and expectations for the economy

186
00:05:44,147 --> 00:05:45,650
are all moving together.

187
00:05:45,650 --> 00:05:47,453
And especially expectations for the economy

188
00:05:47,453 --> 00:05:49,256
should never be taken lightly.

189
00:05:49,256 --> 00:05:51,059
When people buy a home,

190
00:05:51,059 --> 00:05:53,464
they don’t just look at the price.

191
00:05:53,464 --> 00:05:54,816
They also think about

192
00:05:54,816 --> 00:05:57,070
whether their job will stay stable,

193
00:05:57,070 --> 00:05:59,024
whether their income will hold up,

194
00:05:59,024 --> 00:06:01,278
and whether unexpected expenses might rise.

195
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:03,532
Even if the base rate stays the same,

196
00:06:03,532 --> 00:06:06,087
if confidence in the economy is weak,

197
00:06:06,087 --> 00:06:08,642
it’s hard to take on a big loan.

198
00:06:08,642 --> 00:06:11,197
That’s a very realistic judgment.

199
00:06:11,197 --> 00:06:14,504
Right now, instead of jumping in aggressively,

200
00:06:14,504 --> 00:06:15,706
a lot of people are waiting for clearer signals.

201
00:06:15,706 --> 00:06:17,960
That’s why the market

202
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:19,463
is moving more slowly than expected.

203
00:06:19,463 --> 00:06:21,417
On the surface, it looks quiet,

204
00:06:21,417 --> 00:06:23,671
but underneath,

205
00:06:23,671 --> 00:06:25,474
it’s choosing signals very carefully.

206
00:06:25,474 --> 00:06:26,977
There’s one more thing to watch,

207
00:06:26,977 --> 00:06:28,179
and that’s the direction of sentiment.

208
00:06:28,179 --> 00:06:30,734
The real estate market

209
00:06:30,734 --> 00:06:32,237
always moves with both hope and anxiety.

210
00:06:32,237 --> 00:06:34,191
A rate pause is definitely

211
00:06:34,191 --> 00:06:35,393
not all bad news.

212
00:06:35,393 --> 00:06:37,196
But at the same time,

213
00:06:37,196 --> 00:06:39,150
it’s not immediately

214
00:06:39,150 --> 00:06:41,705
a strong positive signal either.

215
00:06:41,705 --> 00:06:43,358
Because a pause can mean

216
00:06:43,358 --> 00:06:46,063
things are stable enough to stop,

217
00:06:46,063 --> 00:06:47,115
but it can also mean

218
00:06:47,115 --> 00:06:49,520
policymakers still aren’t confident enough

219
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:51,774
to make the next move.

220
00:06:51,774 --> 00:06:54,179
And right now,

221
00:06:54,179 --> 00:06:55,381
the market is leaning more toward that second interpretation.

222
00:06:55,381 --> 00:06:56,733
This isn’t a market charging ahead with confidence,

223
00:06:56,733 --> 00:06:58,236
but one moving carefully and checking as it goes.

224
00:06:58,236 --> 00:07:00,039
That’s why the response

225
00:07:00,039 --> 00:07:01,391
is split by region,

226
00:07:01,391 --> 00:07:04,247
split by buyer group,

227
00:07:04,247 --> 00:07:06,050
and even split by price range.

228
00:07:06,050 --> 00:07:08,004
Let’s sum it up.

229
00:07:08,004 --> 00:07:09,657
*Keeping the base rate at 2.5%*

230
00:07:09,657 --> 00:07:11,611
isn’t automatically bullish,

231
00:07:11,611 --> 00:07:13,114
and it isn’t automatically bearish either.

232
00:07:13,114 --> 00:07:15,218
If anything, it’s closer to

233
00:07:15,218 --> 00:07:17,472
a signal that the market

234
00:07:17,472 --> 00:07:19,426
still doesn’t have conviction.

235
00:07:19,426 --> 00:07:21,229
What moves home prices now

236
00:07:21,229 --> 00:07:23,634
is no longer just one line about the base rate.

237
00:07:23,634 --> 00:07:25,738
*Mortgage rates* matter,

238
00:07:25,738 --> 00:07:27,541
*transaction volume* matters,

239
00:07:27,541 --> 00:07:28,593
and local *supply and demand* matters.

240
00:07:28,593 --> 00:07:30,396
And expectations

241
00:07:30,396 --> 00:07:31,748
for an economic recovery

242
00:07:31,748 --> 00:07:34,153
also matter.

243
00:07:34,153 --> 00:07:35,505
In the end, right now,

244
00:07:35,505 --> 00:07:37,609
it matters far more

245
00:07:37,609 --> 00:07:39,863
to read where the market

246
00:07:39,863 --> 00:07:41,215
starts responding first

247
00:07:41,215 --> 00:07:43,920
than to focus on rates alone.

248
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:45,573
More than the headline,

249
00:07:45,573 --> 00:07:48,429
you need to watch what’s happening on the ground.

250
00:07:48,429 --> 00:07:50,533
More than any single number,

251
00:07:50,533 --> 00:07:53,088
you need to watch how the signals connect.

252
00:07:53,088 --> 00:07:55,042
That’s how you can read

253
00:07:55,042 --> 00:07:56,244
today’s market

254
00:07:56,244 --> 00:07:58,348
more accurately.

255
00:07:58,348 --> 00:07:59,851
What’s your area like right now?
